pples with contemporary efforts to mobilize human dignity as a counter-response to the biopolitics of the human body, and the breakdowns this has generated. To do this, he investigates how actors in pivotal institutions -the Vatican, the United Nations, U.S. Federal Bioethics-reconceived human dignity as the bearer of intrinsic worth, only to become frustrated by the Sisyphean struggle of turning its conceptions into practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aBioethics. 0aHuman rights. 0aRespect for persons. 4aAnthropology. 4aBioethics. 4aTheology. 70(DE-588)4006791-90(DE-627)1045852340(DE-576)208867074aBioethik2gnd 70(DE-588)4038654-50(DE-627)1062312190(DE-576)209031360aMenschenwürde2gnd 7aMEDICAL / Ethics.2bisacsh  aBioethics.  aCommission on Human Rights.  aHuman Dignity.  aPresident's Council on Bioethics.  aVatican II.  aanthropology.  abiopower.  ahuman rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107290300 cprintz978082326777440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823267798?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823267798zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823267798/original  a978-3-11-072903-0 Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA